Problem

Filtering on multiple columns from different tables in CALCULATE does not behave like typical column filters.

Example (❌ incorrect):

CALCULATE (
    [Sales Amount],
    Product[Brand] = "Contoso" && Customer[Continent] = "North America",
    Product[Brand] = "Litware" && Customer[Continent] = "Europe"
)

This fails logically because:

CALCULATE combines filter arguments with AND
You end up requiring:
Brand = Contoso AND Brand = Litware → impossible

Correct Concept

When filtering across multiple tables, you must express the filter as a set of valid combinations (tuples):
(Brand, Continent)
Not independent filters on each column
Pattern 1 — CROSSJOIN + FILTER (General Case)
CALCULATE (
    [Sales Amount],
    FILTER (
        CROSSJOIN (
            ALL ( Product[Brand] ),
            ALL ( Customer[Continent] )
        ),
        ( Product[Brand] = "Contoso" && Customer[Continent] = "North America" )
            || ( Product[Brand] = "Litware" && Customer[Continent] = "Europe" )
    )
)
🔍 Behavior
Formula Engine:
Scans both columns
Builds all combinations
Filters down to valid tuples
Storage Engine:
Receives filtered tuple set

⚠️ Cost
Multiple SE scans
FE preparation overhead
Poorer performance when domains grow

Pattern 2 — TREATAS with Tuple Literals (Preferred when possible)
CALCULATE (
    [Sales Amount],
    TREATAS (
        {
            ( "Contoso", "North America" ),
            ( "Litware", "Europe" )
        },
        Product[Brand],
        Customer[Continent]
    )
)
🔍 Behavior
FE does not need to build combinations
Tuple set is already known
Passed directly to SE
✅ Result
Fewer SE scans (often 1)
Cleaner xmSQL
Better performance
xmSQL Evidence

Efficient plan generates:

WHERE
    ('Product'[Brand], 'Customer'[Continent]) IN ( ... )

Important:

This is not a boolean predicate pushdown
It is a tuple filter applied by the storage engine

Key Insight (from SQLBI)

Multi-column filters are not pushed as boolean expressions.
The Formula Engine prepares a set of allowed tuples,
which is then applied by the Storage Engine.

Performance Comparison
Pattern	FE Work	SE Queries	Notes
CROSSJOIN + FILTER	High	Multiple	Builds combinations
TREATAS (tuples)	Low	Minimal (often 1)	Best when tuples known
When to Use What
Use TREATAS when:
You know the exact combinations
Tuple set is small and static
You want best performance
Use CROSSJOIN + FILTER when:
Tuples are dynamic
Need to derive combinations from data
Logic depends on context
